posts.name:
Jen Allen-Knuth
Jen Allen-Knuth
posts.content:
Is there a secret cash prize for B2B companies who use the words "revolutionize" or "transform" in websites, ads, and webinar invites?

These words are intended to be positive.

But, personally, I think they scream "this solution is going to be a lot of work to implement".

Here's an example.

In December, I ate like a bear preparing to hibernate. My diet was bad. Obviously, I wanted that to stop.

So, if I had to choose between clicking on:

"Transform Your Body In 90 Days"

or

"5 Surprisingly High Calorie Meals To Avoid at O'Hare Airport"

I'm picking the latter.

Because Jan-March is my busiest quarter. The language of "transform" suggests it's going to involve a lot of work.

And, the 2nd option isn't pitching a solution in the copy.

It's illuminating a problem I hadn't considered (ex: maybe I thought a taco salad was a healthy choice, until I saw the calorie count of the deep friend salad shell). That sparks curiosity. It's taking me down a path to learn with them.

Now, if at the end of that article, it linked to a paid meal plan solution with healthy options at all major US airports - I might click into that to learn more, and, maybe, buy it.

But, first, I have to feel like there's something they know that I don't. AND, I have to feel like it's not going to be an ungodly amount of effort to get there.

Maybe I'm totally wrong here.

But, JOLT Effect taught us that 40-60% of B2B opps are lost to no-decision.

Our buyers are overwhelmed. We often lose to "it's too expensive" (aka I'm worried we won't be able to do what is necessary to realize the full value) or "it's too much to add to our plates right now" (aka we're already swamped - do I want to add one more thing).

I don't think "transform" and "revolutionize" help our case.

What do you think?

posts.content:
11 Signs You Might Be A Micromanager

(and how to stop yourself)

A micromanager is someone you pay
To watch your top talent walk away.

Spot these subtle signs of micromanagement:

1. You can't go on vacation
üü• Decision-making stops in your absence.
 Build a team that runs without you

2. You only hear "Yes"
üü• Constant agreement masks fear.
 Thank those who challenge you.

3. You are the bottleneck
üü• Everything waits for your approval.
 Trust reversible decisions.

4. You can't think of the last question you asked
üü• All direction, no curiosity.
 Ask, "What are we missing?"

5. You never see mistakes
üü• No risks, no innovation.
 Make failure safe - lead by example.

6. Your best talent leaves
üü• Top talent craves freedom.
 Give trust, not orders.

7. You are in back-to-back meetings
üü• Meetings replace trust.
 Opt out of meetings that don't need you.

8. Your meetings are quiet
üü• Silent teams are scared teams.
 Ensure everyone's input.

9. You discourage skip-level meetings
üü• All communication flows through you.
 Create direct connections.

10. You can't name your employee's kids
üü• Distance creates disconnection.
 Learn what drives each person

11. You're on the edge of burnout
üü• Control drains everyone.
 Model work-life boundaries.

Remember:

Strong teams are built on trust, not control.

Ô∏è Share to help someone
 Followfor more

Scaling happens when you build systems and trust that allow decisions to flow seamlessly, enabling faster execution and sustainable growth. Letting go is a key leadership move.
